"Story": {
    "eyebrow": "The Story",
    "title": "The 1891 blueprint. And a touch of bureaucracy.",
    "p1": "Coincidences don't exist. When we opened Separé in Mikulandská, we had no idea this building had been destined for good drinking since the late 19th century. It took a trip to the old archives to reveal just how close it once came.",
    "p2": "In October 1891, the building owner, Mr. J. F. Tomaschek, filed a permit with the Prague magistrate. He had a clear vision: he wanted to pour and sell wine right here. But he ran straight into the brick wall of Austro-Hungarian bureaucracy.",
    "p3a": "The authorities demanded fees and exhausting conditions that were likely impossible to meet at the time. On a yellowed document from 1895, a brief, handwritten full stop closes the entire project: ",
    "p3quote": "“The wine bar was never established.”",
    "p4a": "It took long decades before a proper toast was finally raised in this building. And even though today we don't pretend to be a classic wine bar — we pour craft beers, open a wild pet-nat, and fill our tables with board games — we're certain of one thing. ",
    "p4highlight": "Mr. Tomaschek would have loved this little place.",
    "epilogue": "We simply finished what started in 1891. Just with better drinks — and without the imperial stamp."
},
